recordings.file-name: XC189178-KINGLET_Gol-cro_s_partial Beaver L Rec Liard H 500m 061614 0438.mp3
recordings.rmk: After forum discussion 9648 and further checking of recordings, I am re-re-identifying, back to the original idea of Bay-breasted Warbler, with thanks to Andrew Spencer for spotting the mistake and suggesting the solution.  We saw Golden-crowned Kinglets in this spot, and this vocalization is similar to Golden-crowned Kinglet in note shape, from which I went down the wrong path.  This is a known location for Bay-breasted in some years, although we did not actually see the species here.

recordings.loc: Silvergate Neighborhood, San Diego, San Diego County, California
recordings.rmk: High pass filter (4000hz, 6dB rolloff). Amplified (20dB). Same individual as XC373794. Intermittently singing on arrival. Initially thought it was a weird AMRE since a singing male had recently been reported in the area.  After a while, I tried using AMRE playback to confirm.  The bird had been quiet, but seemed to respond by singing again and coming a little closer.  Eventually got a brief look at the bird and realized it was a BBWA.  After the bird disappeared again, I briefly played BBWA song one time, but he did not respond.  Maybe 10-15 mins or so after use of playback is when I started recording the bird.

recordings.rmk: Recorded with Canon EOS Rebel T3i built-in mic. Filtered for noise and slightly amplified with Audacity. Habitat: Relatively mature mixed oak. "Central park" type effect with migrants like these here.  Singing amongst cacophony of catbirds. Behavior: Preening often, occasionally chasing other warblers out of area. Otherwise sitting still for extended periods of time. Plumage: Adult male. Conditions: Calm, warm morning, slightly cloudy
